# RESTORE-DETECT-VERIFY: A Quality-Adaptive, Evidence-Grade Traffic Violation Vision System for Indian Roads

## TL;DR
- **Build "AGASTYA"** — a quality-adaptive cascade: a lightweight gating module routes only degraded crops through NAFNet deblurring and a fine-tuned Real-ESRGAN super-resolution stage, feeds restored images to a **YOLOv11-based detector trained with a restoration-aware + MPDIoU/WIoU multi-task loss**, associates riders to motorcycles via **SAM 2 masks**, reads plates with **PARSeq**, and ends in a **C2PA tamper-evident evidence chain**. The novelty is the *closed restoration→detection→verification loop optimized jointly for machine perception (downstream mAP/OCR), not human PSNR*, plus a cryptographically verifiable evidence artifact — a combination absent from the helmet/triple-riding literature.
- **Train on a single 12–24 GB consumer GPU.** Core models (YOLOv11-s/m, NAFNet-width32, fine-tuned Real-ESRGAN, PARSeq OCR) each fit in 8–16 GB with mixed precision; SAM 2 and the diffusion-SR option are inference-only/optional. The defensible flagship dataset stack is **IDD (India Driving Dataset) + AI City Challenge 2024 Track 5 (Indian helmet videos) + an Indian ANPR set**, combined and re-annotated with helmet/no-helmet and trapezium triple-riding boxes.
- **Drop KAN from the critical path** (controlled studies show it loses to MLP at equal budget on vision, and an unoptimized Kolmogorov–Arnold Transformer trains ~123× slower than an equivalent ViT); keep it only as an *optional, ablation-only* lightweight classification head to claim novelty if time permits. Win the evaluation by proving each novel block against an honest YOLO+OCR baseline on the PS metrics (mAP, P/R/F1) plus a **degradation-stratified mAP sweep** and an **OCR-accuracy-vs-resolution curve**.

## Key Findings

**1. The obvious baseline (YOLO + Tesseract OCR) is what every team will build — and it fails exactly where Indian traffic is hardest.** The literature is saturated with YOLOv5/v8 helmet+triple-riding detectors reporting 94–98% on clean, curated frames, but the same papers concede failure under "low resolution, adverse weather, occlusion, and poor illumination." That gap — robustness to degradation and distance — is the winning wedge, and it maps directly onto the PS's explicit demand for robustness to "low light, rain, shadows, and motion blur."

**2. Restoration genuinely helps downstream detection/OCR, but only if optimized for the machine, not the human eye.** Task-driven restoration work (Task-Driven Super-Resolution; MWFormer's recognition-aware training) shows that maximizing PSNR/SSIM does not maximize detection accuracy, and that restoration tuned with a detection/recognition-aware loss outperforms generic restoration as a pre-processor. This is the scientific backbone of AGASTYA's novelty.

**3. NAFNet is the right deblurring choice for a single GPU.** Per Chen et al., "Simple Baselines for Image Restoration" (ECCV 2022, arXiv:2204.04676), NAFNet reaches **33.69 dB PSNR on GoPro deblurring, exceeding the previous SOTA by 0.38 dB with only 8.4% of its computational cost**. It uses no nonlinear activations (SimpleGate + Simplified Channel Attention) and has small width variants that train comfortably in <16 GB.

**4. For SR on plates/distant riders, use a fine-tuned Real-ESRGAN (and optionally a one-step diffusion SR), not heavy multi-step diffusion.** SR pre-processing measurably lifts OCR: Wang et al. ("An Enhanced Super-Resolution GAN for Improving Image Quality on Construction Vehicle License Plates," Springer 2024) report license-plate text recognition rising **from 65% on original images to 74.5% using super-resolved images** (using ESRGAN). Diffusion methods (SeeSR, SUPIR) give better perceptual quality but are slow and prone to hallucinating characters — unacceptable for legal evidence. Keep diffusion SR as an optional "max-quality" branch only.

**5. YOLOv11 is the pragmatic detector; YOLOv12 and RT-DETRv2 are strong but riskier on a single GPU.** Per Tian, Ye & Doermann (arXiv:2502.12524), **YOLOv12-N achieves 40.6% mAP at 1.64 ms on a T4, outperforming YOLOv10-N/YOLOv11-N by 2.1%/1.2% mAP**, but YOLOv12 is reported (Ultralytics docs) as a community/research release that can exhibit training instability and elevated memory use, with YOLO11 recommended for most production workloads. RT-DETRv2 is NMS-free and elegant but heavier to train. Choose YOLOv11 for stability + small-object heads, with YOLOv12 and RT-DETRv2 as ablation comparisons.

**6. SAM 2 adds real value for rider–motorcycle association and evidence masks** — precise instance masks disambiguate which riders belong to which motorcycle (the crux of triple-riding) and produce clean, auditable evidence overlays. Use it zero-shot/prompted by detector boxes; do not train it.

**7. KAN is a trap for the critical path.** Controlled studies ("KAN or MLP: A Fairer Comparison," arXiv:2407.16674; "KANs for Computer Vision: An Experimental Study," arXiv:2411.18224) show KAN underperforms MLP at equal parameter/FLOP budget on vision and is hard to train on standard hardware. Per Raffel & Chen, "FlashKAT" (AAAI 2026, arXiv:2505.13813), **an unoptimized KAT (using GR-KAN) is 123× slower during training than an identically sized ViT on ImageNet-1K**. KAN *heads* help only in bundled, CUDA-optimized designs (GRN-KANformer, Hyb-KAN ViT), where the head's isolated contribution is unproven. Verdict: optional novelty ablation only.

**8. Custom multi-task loss is the cheapest, most defensible novelty.** Replacing CIoU with MPDIoU (Ma & Xu, CVPR 2023) or WIoUv3 measurably helps small/occluded objects; combining that with a restoration-aware perceptual term and focal-style class balancing (helmet-violation and triple-riding are minority classes) gives a genuinely novel, paper-grade objective that costs almost nothing to implement.

## Details

### The problem reframed
The PS asks for a full multi-violation pipeline (helmet, seatbelt, triple-riding, wrong-side, stop-line, red-light, illegal parking) plus ANPR, evidence, and analytics. Doing all seven shallowly is the losing move. The winning move, per the user's own instinct: **ship a deep, polished vertical slice — helmet non-compliance + triple riding + ANPR + evidence generation — that is demonstrably robust to degradation, and architect the rest as clearly-specified extension points.** Helmet and triple-riding are the most India-specific, highest-impact, and best-supported by public data.

### The flagship architecture: AGASTYA (Restore → Detect → Verify)
A four-stage quality-adaptive cascade:

**Stage 0 — Quality gating (novel, cheap).** A tiny no-reference quality head (a 2-layer CNN regressing blur/noise/resolution scores, or a BRISQUE/MANIQA proxy) scores each detected crop. Only crops below threshold are routed to restoration. This keeps latency low and prevents restoration from degrading already-clean images (a documented failure of blanket restoration). This gating is the system's signature efficiency idea and the lever that makes the heavy restoration models affordable in real time.

**Stage 1 — Restoration (NAFNet + Real-ESRGAN).** NAFNet-width32 handles motion blur and noise; a Real-ESRGAN ×4 model, **fine-tuned on a license-plate/rider-crop degradation model** (synthetic motion blur + downscaling + JPEG, per Real-ESRGAN's high-order degradation recipe), upsamples small/distant plates and helmet regions. Both are trained with a restoration-aware loss that includes a detection/recognition feedback term so restored outputs are optimized for the detector and OCR, not for PSNR.

**Stage 2 — Detection + association (YOLOv11 + SAM 2).**
- YOLOv11-m detects {motorcycle, rider, helmet, no-helmet, person, car, truck, bus, auto-rickshaw, license-plate}, with an added P2 small-object head for distant plates/helmets.
- Rider-association: following the IDD motorcycle-violation work (arXiv:2204.08364), use a trapezium box (or SAM 2 mask) for the rider–motorcycle instance to count riders robustly and suppress false positives from adjacent motorcycles — this is how triple-riding is decided (≥3 person instances associated with one motorcycle mask).
- SAM 2, prompted by YOLO boxes, produces precise rider/motorcycle masks for association and for clean evidence overlays.

**Stage 3 — Recognition + classification + confidence.** PARSeq scene-text recognizer (Bautista & Atienza, ECCV 2022) reads the (super-resolved) plate; a violation-classification head assigns violation type with calibrated confidence. For confidence, use **evidential deep learning / temperature-scaled calibration** so the system emits trustworthy scores (the PS explicitly asks for confidence scores) and can abstain on low-evidence cases — a strong "responsible enforcement" story.

**Stage 4 — Evidence chain (novel for this PS).** Each violation produces an annotated image + JSON metadata (timestamp, GPS/camera id, violation class, confidence, plate string, model versions) wrapped in a **C2PA content credential**: a SHA-256 hard binding over the evidence pixels + X.509-signed manifest, making the evidence tamper-evident and court-defensible. No helmet/triple-riding paper in the surveyed literature does this; it is a genuine, demo-able differentiator.

